Chapter 6: Adaptive Error Correction and Operational Stability

6.1 Motivation: Correlated Noise and the Limits of i.i.d. Error Correction

Standard QKD error correction (e.g., Cascade, LDPC) assumes that errors are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) with a fixed QBER Q. When the QBER varies in time or exhibits correlations, the performance degrades because the code cannot adapt to the changing error rate. Moreover, the security proof of BB84 relies on the ability to estimate Q from a random sample; if errors are correlated, the sample may not be representative.

On Mars, dust storms cause QBER to vary from a few percent to over 10 % over minutes to hours. During a storm, the extinction coefficient can change significantly, leading to burst errors. To maintain a positive secure key rate, we need a protocol that can:

· Filter out the slowly varying component of the noise.
· Adapt the encoding rate and mean photon number to optimize throughput.
· Switch modes automatically based on environmental sensors and real‑time QBER estimates.

6.2 Decoherence‑Free Subspace (DFS) for Collective Noise

Consider two qubits undergoing identical unitary rotations U_\theta = e^{-i\theta \sigma_z} (collective dephasing). This is a good model for the effect of slowly varying dust depolarization: the polarization rotation induced by dust particles is the same for photons that traverse the same atmosphere within a short time interval.

The two‑qubit subspace \mathcal{H}_{\text{DFS}} = \text{span}\{|01\rangle, |10\rangle\} is invariant under U_\theta \otimes U_\theta:

U_\theta \otimes U_\theta |01\rangle = e^{-i\theta} e^{i\theta} |01\rangle = |01\rangle,

U_\theta \otimes U_\theta |10\rangle = e^{i\theta} e^{-i\theta} |10\rangle = |10\rangle.

Thus, any state in this subspace is immune to collective dephasing. A logical qubit can be encoded as

|\tilde{0}\rangle = |01\rangle,\quad |\tilde{1}\rangle = |10\rangle.

The encoding rate is 1/2 (two physical qubits per logical qubit).

6.3 Stability Lemma: Quadratic Suppression of Residual Error

We now formalize the noise model and prove that the DFS encoding eliminates the slowly varying component, leaving only the differential jitter.

Noise model: Consider two consecutive pulses with rotation angles \theta_1 and \theta_2. The relative difference \delta = \theta_2 - \theta_1 is small because the atmospheric fluctuation is slow. The absolute magnitude \theta_1 can be large. We treat the noise as a unitary operation U_{\theta_1} \otimes U_{\theta_2} on the two‑qubit state.

Lemma 1 (Stability of DFS‑Decoded Residual Error).
Let a logical qubit be encoded in the DFS \{|01\rangle, |10\rangle\} and transmitted through a channel that applies independent collective rotations U_{\theta_1} = e^{-i\theta_1 \sigma_z} and U_{\theta_2} = e^{-i\theta_2 \sigma_z} to the two physical qubits, with |\theta_2 - \theta_1| = \delta. Then the probability of a logical bit error after decoding is at most \delta^2 for small \delta, independent of \theta_1.

Proof.
An arbitrary logical state is |\psi\rangle_L = \alpha |01\rangle + \beta |10\rangle with |\alpha|^2 + |\beta|^2 = 1. After the noise, the state becomes

|\psi'\rangle = \alpha (U_{\theta_1} \otimes U_{\theta_2}) |01\rangle + \beta (U_{\theta_1} \otimes U_{\theta_2}) |10\rangle.

Using U_{\theta}|0\rangle = e^{-i\theta}|0\rangle and U_{\theta}|1\rangle = e^{i\theta}|1\rangle, we have

(U_{\theta_1} \otimes U_{\theta_2}) |01\rangle = (e^{-i\theta_1}|0\rangle) \otimes (e^{i\theta_2}|1\rangle) = e^{-i\theta_1} e^{i\theta_2} |01\rangle = e^{i(\theta_2 - \theta_1)} |01\rangle,

(U_{\theta_1} \otimes U_{\theta_2}) |10\rangle = e^{i\theta_1} e^{-i\theta_2} |10\rangle = e^{-i(\theta_2 - \theta_1)} |10\rangle.

Let \delta = \theta_2 - \theta_1. Then

|\psi'\rangle = \alpha e^{i\delta} |01\rangle + \beta e^{-i\delta} |10\rangle = e^{i\delta} \left( \alpha |01\rangle + \beta e^{-2i\delta} |10\rangle \right).

Up to a global phase, the state is \alpha |01\rangle + \beta e^{-2i\delta} |10\rangle. This is equivalent to a rotation of the logical qubit by an angle \phi = 2\delta about the Z axis. Measuring the logical qubit in the computational basis (i.e., projecting onto |01\rangle or |10\rangle) yields the probability of a bit error (i.e., measuring the wrong logical state) given by

P_{\text{error}} = \frac{1 - \cos(2\delta)}{2} = \sin^2 \delta.

For small \delta, \sin^2 \delta \approx \delta^2. Hence P_{\text{error}} \le \delta^2. ∎

Corollary: If the variation \delta over the correlation window is bounded by \Delta, then the residual QBER after DFS decoding satisfies Q_{\text{res}} \le \Delta^2.

Thus, the DFS acts as a high‑pass filter: it eliminates the static or slowly varying component of the noise, leaving only the high‑frequency jitter. The residual error scales quadratically with the rate of change of the environment, not its absolute magnitude.

6.4 Operational Constraints Derived from the Lemma

The Stability Lemma provides concrete constraints for system design:

1. Correlation time requirement: For the DFS to be effective, the two physical qubits forming a logical qubit must experience nearly the same rotation. This requires that the time separation between the two pulses, T_{\text{sep}}, satisfy T_{\text{sep}} \ll \tau_c, where \tau_c is the correlation time of the dust density (or the noise process). A safe design sets T_{\text{sep}} \le \tau_c / 100, i.e., the repetition rate f_{\text{rep}} \ge 100 / \tau_c. Typical \tau_c for Martian dust is 0.1–10 s, so f_{\text{rep}} \ge 1 kHz to 100 kHz. Our baseline 1 GHz repetition rate far exceeds this, so the condition is easily satisfied. However, if the link experiences high‑frequency vibrations (e.g., from a dust devil), the effective correlation time decreases; the system must then increase the spacing between the two pulses (i.e., lower the logical repetition rate) to keep them within the same noise bucket.
2. Mean photon number throttling: In storm mode, the encoding rate is halved, so the raw key rate per pulse is reduced. To maintain a positive secure key rate, we may increase the mean photon number \mu from 0.1 to up to 0.3, provided that decoy states are used to bound the multi‑photon component. The optimal \mu balances the detection probability against the multi‑photon attack risk.
3. Residual error threshold: After DFS decoding, the residual QBER Q_{\text{res}} must be low enough to allow privacy amplification. If Q_{\text{res}} > 5\%, the privacy amplification step may fail to produce a secure key; the system should then issue a “Hard Halt” and wait for better conditions.

6.5 Operational Modes and Autonomous Switching

Based on the channel model and the Stability Lemma, we define four operational modes:

Mode Environmental Condition Encoding Repetition Rate (logical) \mu Target Q_{\text{res}} Theoretical Secure Key Rate
Clear Sky Dust OD < 0.1, no solar flare BB84 1 GHz 0.1 < 2 % ~14 Mbit/s
Moderate Dust 0.1 ≤ OD < 0.5 BB84 + LDPC 1 GHz 0.1 < 7 % ~2.6 Mbit/s
