Chapter 8: Performance Estimates and Analytical Bounds

8.1 Theoretical Key Rate Expression

The asymptotic secure key rate per second for a QKD system with sifting and error correction is given by (Shor & Preskill, 2000; Scarani et al., 2009)

R = \frac{1}{2} \, f_{\text{rep}} \, \eta_{\text{total}} \, \mu \, \frac{k}{n} \left[ 1 - f(Q) H_2(Q) \right],

where:

· f_{\text{rep}} is the pulse repetition rate (physical pulses per second),
· \eta_{\text{total}} is the total system efficiency (including atmospheric transmission, optics, and detector efficiency),
· \mu is the mean photon number per pulse,
· k/n is the encoding rate (1 for BB84, 1/2 for DFS),
· f(Q) is the error correction efficiency (≥ 1),
· H_2(x) = -x\log_2 x - (1-x)\log_2(1-x) is the binary entropy function,
· Q is the quantum bit error rate after sifting (or residual QBER after DFS decoding).

This formula is derived under the assumption of an asymptotic, infinite‑key regime. For finite keys, corrections reduce the rate, but the asymptotic expression provides an upper bound and serves as a benchmark.

8.2 Parameter Ranges from Martian Channel Model

Using the channel model developed in Chapter 5, we estimate the ranges of key parameters for three representative conditions. The values are based on literature (Yang et al., 2022; Gao et al., 2022; Liao et al., 2022) and the analytical expressions of Section 5.6.

